🌳 Random Forest Classification for Customer Purchase Prediction

This project demonstrates the implementation of Random Forest Classification to predict whether a customer will purchase a product based on their features.

The goal is to understand how ensemble learning improves model performance and how hyperparameter tuning can optimize results.

🛠️ Libraries Used
Python
NumPy
Pandas
Matplotlib
Scikit-learn
📂 Dataset Description

The dataset contains:

Age
Estimated Salary
Purchased (Target Variable)

Features used:

Age
Estimated Salary

Target:

Purchased (0 or 1)
🔍 Project Workflow
1️⃣ Data Loading & Preparation
Loaded dataset using Pandas
Selected features and target variable
Split dataset into training and testing sets (80–20)
2️⃣ Model Building
Used RandomForestClassifier
Built an ensemble model using multiple decision trees
3️⃣ Hyperparameter Tuning

Used GridSearchCV to find the best parameters:

n_estimators: Number of trees
max_depth: Depth of trees
min_samples_split
min_samples_leaf
max_features

Selected the best model based on accuracy score.

4️⃣ Prediction
Generated predictions on test dataset
Calculated predicted probabilities for ROC analysis
5️⃣ Model Evaluation

The model was evaluated using:

Accuracy Score
Confusion Matrix
ROC-AUC Score
ROC Curve

These metrics help measure classification performance and model reliability.

📊 Visualization
ROC Curve plotted using Matplotlib
Shows trade-off between True Positive Rate and False Positive Rate
🎯 What I Learned
How Random Forest works as an ensemble model
Importance of hyperparameter tuning
How to evaluate classification models using ROC-AUC
Difference between single models and ensemble models
How multiple trees improve prediction stability

This project strengthened my understanding of ensemble-based classification algorithms.
